# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: drizzle-orm
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:drizzle-orm/drizzle-team-drizzle-orm] Drizzle is a modern TypeScript ORM developers wanna use in their next project.
[src:drizzle-orm/drizzle-team-drizzle-orm] It is lightweight at only ~7.4kb minified+gzipped, and it's tree shakeable with exactly 0 dependencies.
[src:drizzle-orm/drizzle-team-drizzle-orm] While you can use Drizzle as a JavaScript library, it shines with TypeScript.
[src:drizzle-orm/drizzle-team-drizzle-orm] It lets you **declare SQL schemas** and build both **relational** and **SQL-like queries**, while keeping the balance between type-safety and extensibility for toolmakers to build on top.
[src:drizzle-orm/drizzle-team-drizzle-orm] While Drizzle ORM remains a thin typed layer on top of SQL, we made a set of tools for people to have best possible developer experience.
[src:drizzle-orm/drizzle-team-drizzle-orm] Drizzle comes with a powerful **Drizzle Kit** CLI companion for you to have hassle-free migrations.
[src:drizzle-orm/drizzle-team-drizzle-orm] It can generate SQL migration files for you or apply schema changes directly to the database.
[src:drizzle-orm/drizzle-team-drizzle-orm] We also have **Drizzle Studio** for you to effortlessly browse and manipulate data in your database of choice.
[src:drizzle-orm/drizzle-team-drizzle-orm] Check out the full documentation on the website.
[src:drizzle-orm/drizzle] While most drizzle has only a minor immediate impact upon humans, freezing drizzle can lead to treacherous conditions.
[src:drizzle-orm/drizzle] Freezing drizzle occurs when supercooled drizzle drops land on a surface whose temperature is below freezing.
[src:drizzle-orm/drizzle] These drops immediately freeze upon impact, leading to the buildup of sheet ice (sometimes called black ice) on the surface of roads.
[src:drizzle-orm/drizzle] Drizzle tends to be the most frequent form of precipitation over large areas of the world's oceans, particularly in the colder regions of the subtropics.
[src:drizzle-orm/drizzle] These regions are dominated by shallow marine stratocumulus and trade wind cumulus clouds, which exist entirely within the marine boundary layer.
[src:drizzle-orm/drizzle] Despite the low rates of surface accumulation, drizzle exerts a major influence over the structure, coverage, and radiative properties of clouds in these regions.
[src:drizzle-orm/drizzle] This has motivated scientists to design more sophisticated and sensitive instruments such as high-frequency radars which can detect drizzle.
[src:drizzle-orm/drizzle] These studies have shown that the quantity of drizzle is strongly linked to cloud morphology and tends to be associated with updrafts within the marine boundary layer.
[src:drizzle-orm/drizzle] Increased amounts of drizzle tend to be found in marine clouds that form in clean air masses that have low concentrations of cloud droplets.
[src:drizzle-orm/drizzle] This interconnection between clouds and drizzle can be explored using high-resolution numerical modelling such as large eddy simulation.
[src:drizzle-orm/drizzle] It has been hypothesized by a group of atmospheric scientists at Texas A&M University that particulates in the atmosphere caused by human activities may suppress drizzle.
[src:drizzle-orm/drizzle] According to this hypothesis, because drizzle can be an effective means of removing moisture from a cloud, its suppression could help to increase the thickness, coverage, and longevity of marine stratocumulus clouds.
[src:drizzle-orm/drizzle] This would lead to increased cloud albedo on a regional to global scale, and a cooling effect on the atmosphere.
[src:drizzle-orm/drizzle] Estimates using complex global climate models suggest that this effect may be partially masking the effects of greenhouse gas increases on global surface temperature.
[src:drizzle-orm/drizzle] However, it is not clear that the representation of the chemical and physical processes needed to accurately simulate the interaction between aerosols, clouds, and drizzle in current (as of 2005) climate models is sufficient to fully understand the global impacts of changes in particulates.
[src:drizzle-orm/global-objects-object] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:drizzle-orm/global-objects-object] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:drizzle-orm/global-objects-object] The **`Object`** type represents one of JavaScript's data types.
[src:drizzle-orm/global-objects-object] It is used to store various keyed collections and more complex entities.
[src:drizzle-orm/global-objects-object] Objects can be created using the `Object()` constructor or the object initializer / literal syntax.
[src:drizzle-orm/global-objects-object] Nearly all objects in JavaScript are instances of `Object`; a typical object inherits properties (including methods) from `Object.prototype`, although these properties may be shadowed (a.k.a. overridden).
[src:drizzle-orm/global-objects-object] The only objects that don't inherit from `Object.prototype` are those with `null` prototype, or descended from other `null` prototype objects.
[src:drizzle-orm/global-objects-object] Changes to the `Object.prototype` object are seen by **all** objects through prototype chaining, unless the properties and methods subject to those changes are overridden further along the prototype chain.
[src:drizzle-orm/global-objects-object] This provides a very powerful although potentially dangerous mechanism to override or extend object behavior.
[src:drizzle-orm/global-objects-object] To make it more secure, `Object.prototype` is the only object in the core JavaScript language that has immutable prototype — the prototype of `Object.prototype` is always `null` and not changeable.
[src:drizzle-orm/global-objects-object] You should avoid calling any of the `Object.prototype` methods directly from the instance, especially those that are not intended to be polymorphic (i.e., only its initial behavior makes sense and no descending object could override it in a meaningful way).
[src:drizzle-orm/global-objects-object] All objects descending from `Object.prototype` may define a custom own property that has the same name, but with entirely different semantics from what you expect.
[src:drizzle-orm/global-objects-object] Furthermore, these properties are not inherited by `null`-prototype objects.
[src:drizzle-orm/global-objects-object] All modern JavaScript utilities for working with objects are static.
[src:drizzle-orm/global-objects-object] There isn't any method in an Object itself to delete its own properties (such as `Map.prototype.delete()`).
[src:drizzle-orm/global-objects-object] To do so, one must use the `delete` operator.
[src:drizzle-orm/global-objects-object] Almost all objects in JavaScript ultimately inherit from `Object.prototype` (see inheritance and the prototype chain).
[src:drizzle-orm/global-objects-object] However, you may create `null`-prototype objects using `Object.create(null)` or the object initializer syntax with `__proto__: null` (note: the `__proto__` key in object literals is different from the deprecated `Object.prototype.__proto__` property).
[src:drizzle-orm/global-objects-object] You can also change the prototype of an existing object to `null` by calling `Object.setPrototypeOf(obj, null)`.
[src:drizzle-orm/global-objects-object] An object with a `null` prototype can behave in unexpected ways, because it doesn't inherit any object methods from `Object.prototype`.
[src:drizzle-orm/global-objects-object] This is especially true when debugging, since common object-property converting/detecting utility functions may generate errors, or lose information (especially if using silent error-traps that ignore errors).
[src:drizzle-orm/global-objects-object] Unlike normal objects, in which `toString()` is on the object's prototype, the `toString()` method here is an own property of `nullProtoObj`.
[src:drizzle-orm/global-objects-object] This is because `nullProtoObj` has no (`null`) prototype.
[src:drizzle-orm/global-objects-object] You can also revert a null-prototype object back to an ordinary object using `Object.setPrototypeOf(nullProtoObj, Object.prototype)`.
[src:drizzle-orm/global-objects-object] In practice, objects with `null` prototype are usually used as a cheap substitute for maps.
[src:drizzle-orm/global-objects-object] In such case, the addition of any method should be done cautiously, as they can be confused with the other key-value pairs stored as data.
[src:drizzle-orm/global-objects-object] Making your object not inherit from `Object.prototype` also prevents prototype pollution attacks.
[src:drizzle-orm/global-objects-object] If a malicious script adds a property to `Object.prototype`, it will be accessible on every object in your program, except objects that have null prototype.
[src:drizzle-orm/global-objects-object] JavaScript also has built-in APIs that produce `null`-prototype objects, especially those that use objects as ad hoc key-value collections.
[src:drizzle-orm/global-objects-object] The term "`null`-prototype object" often also includes any object without `Object.prototype` in its prototype chain.
[src:drizzle-orm/global-objects-object] Such objects can be created with `extends null` when using classes.
[src:drizzle-orm/global-objects-object] Many built-in operations that expect objects first coerce their arguments to objects.
[src:drizzle-orm/global-objects-object] There are two ways to achieve nearly the same effect in JavaScript.
[src:drizzle-orm/global-objects-object] Unlike conversion to primitives, the object coercion process itself is not observable in any way, since it doesn't invoke custom code like `toString` or `valueOf` methods.
