[src:drizzle-orm/global-objects-object] You can use the `Object()` constructor to create an object wrapper of a primitive value.
[src:drizzle-orm/global-objects-object] When altering the behavior of existing `Object.prototype` methods, consider injecting code by wrapping your extension before or after the existing logic.
[src:drizzle-orm/global-objects-object] For example, this (untested) code will pre-conditionally execute custom logic before the built-in logic or someone else's extension is executed.
[src:drizzle-orm/global-objects-object] When modifying prototypes with hooks, pass `this` and the arguments (the call state) to the current behavior by calling `apply()` on the function.
[src:drizzle-orm/global-objects-object] This pattern can be used for any prototype, such as `Node.prototype`, `Function.prototype`, etc.
[src:drizzle-orm/global-objects-object] You can read more about prototypes in Inheritance and the prototype chain.
[src:drizzle-orm/object-relational-mapping] In object-oriented programming, data-management tasks act on objects that combine scalar values into objects.
[src:drizzle-orm/object-relational-mapping] For example, consider an address book entry that represents a single person along with zero or more phone numbers and zero or more addresses.
[src:drizzle-orm/object-relational-mapping] This could be modeled in an object-oriented implementation by a "Person object" with an attribute/field to hold each data item that the entry comprises: the person's name, a list of phone numbers, and a list of addresses.
[src:drizzle-orm/object-relational-mapping] The list of phone numbers would itself contain "PhoneNumber objects" and so on.
[src:drizzle-orm/object-relational-mapping] Each such address-book entry is treated as a single object by the programming language (it can be referenced by a single variable containing a pointer to the object, for instance).
[src:drizzle-orm/object-relational-mapping] Various methods can be associated with the object, such as methods to return the preferred phone number, the home address, and so on.
[src:drizzle-orm/object-relational-mapping] By contrast, relational databases, such as SQL, group scalars into tuples, which are then enumerated in tables.
[src:drizzle-orm/object-relational-mapping] Tuples and objects have some general similarity, in that they are both ways to collect values into named fields such that the whole collection can be manipulated as a single compound entity.
[src:drizzle-orm/object-relational-mapping] They have many differences, though, in particular: lifecycle management (row insertion and deletion, versus garbage collection or reference counting), references to other entities (object references, versus foreign key references), and inheritance (non-existent in relational databases).
[src:drizzle-orm/object-relational-mapping] As well, objects are managed on-heap and are under full control of a single process, while database tuples are shared and must incorporate locking, merging, and retry.
[src:drizzle-orm/object-relational-mapping] Object–relational mapping provides automated support for mapping tuples to objects and back, while accounting for all of these differences.
[src:drizzle-orm/object-relational-mapping] The heart of the problem involves translating the logical representation of the objects into an atomized form that is capable of being stored in the database while preserving the properties of the objects and their relationships so that they can be reloaded as objects when needed.
[src:drizzle-orm/object-relational-mapping] If this storage and retrieval functionality is implemented, the objects are said to be persistent.
[src:drizzle-orm/object-relational-mapping] Implementation-specific details of storage drivers are generally wrapped in an API in the programming language in use, exposing methods to interact with the storage medium in a way which is simpler and more in line with the paradigms of surrounding code.
[src:drizzle-orm/object-relational-mapping] The following is a simple example, written in C# code, to execute a query written in SQL using a database engine.
[src:drizzle-orm/object-relational-mapping] In contrast, the following makes use of an ORM-job API which makes it possible to write code that naturally makes use of the features of the language.
[src:drizzle-orm/object-relational-mapping] The case above makes use of an object representing the storage repository and methods of that object.
[src:drizzle-orm/object-relational-mapping] Other frameworks might provide code as static methods, as in the example below, and yet other methods may not implement an object-oriented system at all.
[src:drizzle-orm/object-relational-mapping] Often the choice of paradigm is made for the best fit of the ORM into the surrounding language's design principles.
[src:drizzle-orm/object-relational-mapping] Compared to traditional techniques of exchange between an object-oriented language and a relational database, ORM often reduces the amount of code that needs to be written.
[src:drizzle-orm/object-relational-mapping] Disadvantages of ORM tools generally stem from the high level of abstraction obscuring what is actually happening in the implementation code.
[src:drizzle-orm/object-relational-mapping] Another approach is to use an object-oriented database management system (OODBMS) or document-oriented databases such as native XML databases that provide more flexibility in data modeling.
[src:drizzle-orm/object-relational-mapping] OODBMSs are databases designed specifically for working with object-oriented values.
[src:drizzle-orm/object-relational-mapping] Using an OODBMS eliminates the need for converting data to and from its SQL form, as the data is stored in its original object representation and relationships are directly represented, rather than requiring join tables/operations.
[src:drizzle-orm/object-relational-mapping] The equivalent of ORMs for document-oriented databases are called object-document mappers (ODMs).
[src:drizzle-orm/object-relational-mapping] Document-oriented databases also prevent the user from having to "shred" objects into table rows.
[src:drizzle-orm/object-relational-mapping] Many of these systems also support the XQuery query language to retrieve datasets.
[src:drizzle-orm/object-relational-mapping] Object-oriented databases tend to be used in complex, niche applications.
[src:drizzle-orm/object-relational-mapping] One of the arguments against using an OODBMS is that it may not be able to execute ad-hoc, application-independent queries.
[src:drizzle-orm/object-relational-mapping] For this reason, many programmers find themselves more at home with an object-SQL mapping system, even though most object-oriented databases are able to process SQL queries to a limited extent.
[src:drizzle-orm/object-relational-mapping] Other OODBMS provide replication to SQL databases, as a means of addressing the need for ad-hoc queries, while preserving well-known query patterns.
[src:drizzle-orm/object-relational-mapping] A variety of difficulties arise when considering how to match an object system to a relational database.
[src:drizzle-orm/object-relational-mapping] These difficulties are referred to as the object–relational impedance mismatch.
[src:drizzle-orm/object-relational-mapping] An alternative to implementing ORM is use of the native procedural languages provided with every major database.
[src:drizzle-orm/object-relational-mapping] These can be called from the client using SQL statements.
[src:drizzle-orm/object-relational-mapping] The Data Access Object (DAO) design pattern is used to abstract these statements and offer a lightweight object-oriented interface to the rest of the application.
[src:drizzle-orm/object-relational-mapping] ORMs are limited to their predefined functionality, which may not cover all edge cases or database features.
[src:drizzle-orm/object-relational-mapping] They usually mitigate this limitation by providing users with an interface to write raw queries, such as Django ORM.
[src:drizzle-orm/overview] It looks and feels simple, performs on day *1000* of your project, lets you do things your way, and is there when you need it.
[src:drizzle-orm/overview] First and foremost, Drizzle is a library and a collection of complementary opt-in tools.
[src:drizzle-orm/overview] With data frameworks you have to build projects **around them** and not **with them**.
[src:drizzle-orm/overview] Other ORMs and data frameworks tend to deviate/abstract you away from SQL, which leads to a double learning curve: needing to know both SQL and the framework’s API.
[src:drizzle-orm/overview] We embrace SQL and built Drizzle to be SQL-like at its core, so you can have zero to no learning curve and access to the full power of SQL.
[src:drizzle-orm/overview] We’re always striving for a perfectly balanced solution, and while SQL-like does cover 100% of the needs, there are certain common scenarios where you can query data in a better way.
[src:drizzle-orm/overview] We’ve built the **Queries API** for you, so you can fetch relational nested data from the database in the most convenient and performant way, and never think about joins and data mapping.
[src:drizzle-orm/overview] Drizzle ORM is dialect-specific, slim, performant and serverless-ready **by design**.
[src:drizzle-orm/overview] We’ve spent a lot of time to make sure you have best-in-class SQL dialect support, including Postgres, MySQL, and others.
[src:drizzle-orm/overview] Drizzle operates natively through industry-standard database drivers.
[src:drizzle-orm/overview] We support all major **PostgreSQL**, **MySQL**, **SQLite**, **SingleStore**, **MSSQL** or **CockroachDB** drivers out there, and we’re adding new ones **really fast**.
[src:drizzle-orm/overview] More and more companies are adopting Drizzle in production, experiencing immense benefits in both DX and performance.
[src:drizzle-orm/overview] We have an outstanding **Discord community** and welcome all builders to our **Twitter**.
[src:drizzle-orm/overview] Next.js Project with Vercel, Neon, Drizzle, TailwindCSS, FlowBite and more!
[src:drizzle-orm/overview] Drizzle ORM First impressions - migrations, relations, queries!
[src:drizzle-orm/query-language] A **query language**, also known as **data query language** or **database query language** (**DQL**), is a computer language used to make queries in databases and information systems.
[src:drizzle-orm/query-language] In database systems, query languages rely on strict theory to retrieve information.
[src:drizzle-orm/query-language] A well known example is the Structured Query Language (SQL).
[src:drizzle-orm/query-language] Broadly, query languages can be classified according to whether they are *database* query languages or *information retrieval* query languages.
[src:drizzle-orm/query-language] The difference is that a **database query language** attempts to give factual answers to factual questions, while an **information retrieval query language** attempts to find documents containing information that is relevant to an area of inquiry.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] Introduced in the 1970s, SQL offered two main advantages over older read–write APIs such as ISAM or VSAM.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] Firstly, it introduced the concept of accessing many records with one single command.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] Secondly, it eliminates the need to specify *how* to reach a record, i.e., with or without an index.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] Originally based upon relational algebra and tuple relational calculus, SQL consists of many types of statements, which may be informally classed as sublanguages, commonly: data query language (DQL), data definition language (DDL), data control language (DCL), and data manipulation language (DML).
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] The scope of SQL includes data query, data manipulation (insert, update, and delete), data definition (schema creation and modification), and data access control.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] Although SQL is essentially a declarative language (4GL), it also includes procedural elements.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] SQL was one of the first commercial languages to use Edgar F.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] The model was described in his influential 1970 paper, "A Relational Model of Data for Large Shared Data Banks".
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] Despite not entirely adhering to the relational model as described by Codd, SQL became the most widely used database language.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] SQL became a standard of the American National Standards Institute (ANSI) in 1986 and of the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) in 1987.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] Since then, the standard has been revised multiple times to include a larger set of features and incorporate common extensions.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] Despite the existence of standards, virtually no implementations in existence adhere to it fully, and most SQL code requires at least some changes before being ported to different database systems.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] SQL was initially developed at IBM by Donald D.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] Boyce after learning about the relational model from Edgar F.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] This version, initially called SEQUEL (Structured English Query Language), was designed to manipulate and retrieve data stored in IBM's original quasirelational database management system, System R, which a group at IBM San Jose Research Laboratory had developed during the 1970s.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] Chamberlin and Boyce's first attempt at a relational database language was SQUARE (Specifying Queries in A Relational Environment), but it was difficult to use due to subscript/superscript notation.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] After moving to the San Jose Research Laboratory in 1973, they began work on a sequel to SQUARE.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] The original name SEQUEL, which is widely regarded as a pun on QUEL, the query language of Ingres, was later changed to SQL (dropping the vowels) because "SEQUEL" was a trademark of the UK-based Hawker Siddeley Dynamics Engineering Limited company.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] The label SQL later became the acronym for Structured Query Language.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] After testing SQL at customer test sites to determine the usefulness and practicality of the system, IBM began developing commercial products based on their System R prototype, including System/38, SQL/DS, and IBM Db2, which were commercially available in 1979, 1981, and 1983, respectively.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] IBM's endorsement caused the industry to move to SQL from alternatives like QUEL.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] In the late 1970s, Relational Software, Inc.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] (now Oracle Corporation) saw the potential of the concepts described by Codd, Chamberlin, and Boyce, and developed their own SQL-based RDBMS with aspirations of selling it to the U.S.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] Navy, Central Intelligence Agency, and other U.S. government agencies.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] In June 1979, Relational Software introduced one of the first commercially available implementations of SQL, Oracle V2 (Version2) for VAX computers.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] By 1986, ANSI and ISO standard groups officially adopted the standard "Database Language SQL" language definition.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] SQL implementations are incompatible between vendors and do not necessarily completely follow standards.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] In particular, date and time syntax, string concatenation, `NULL`s, and comparison case sensitivity vary from vendor to vendor.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] PostgreSQL and Mimer SQL strive for standards compliance, though PostgreSQL does not adhere to the standard in all cases.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] For example, the folding of unquoted names to lower case in PostgreSQL is incompatible with the SQL standard, which says that unquoted names should be folded to upper case.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] Thus, according to the standard, `Foo` should be equivalent to `FOO`, not `foo`.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] Popular implementations of SQL commonly omit support for basic features of Standard SQL, such as the `DATE` or `TIME` data types.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] The most obvious such examples, and incidentally the most popular commercial and proprietary SQL DBMSs, are Oracle (whose `DATE` behaves as `DATETIME`, and lacks a `TIME` type) and MS SQL Server (before the 2008 version).
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] As a result, SQL code can rarely be ported between database systems without modifications.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] SQL was adopted as a standard by the ANSI in 1986 as SQL-86 and the ISO in 1987.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] It is maintained by *ISO/IEC JTC 1, Information technology, Subcommittee SC 32, Data management and interchange*.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] Until 1996, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) data-management standards program certified SQL DBMS compliance with the SQL standard.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] Vendors now self-certify the compliance of their products.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] The original standard declared that the official pronunciation for "SQL" was an initialism: /ˌɛsˌkjuːˈɛl/ ("ess cue el").
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] Regardless, many English-speaking database professionals (including Donald Chamberlin himself) use the acronym-like pronunciation of /ˈsiːkwəl/ ("sequel"), mirroring the language's prerelease development name, "SEQUEL".
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] The standard is commonly denoted by the pattern: *ISO/IEC 9075-n:yyyy Part n: title*, or, as a shortcut, *ISO/IEC 9075*.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] Interested parties may purchase the standards documents from ISO, IEC, or ANSI.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] SQL is designed for a specific purpose: to query data contained in a relational database.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] SQL is a set-based, declarative programming language, not an imperative programming language like C or BASIC.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] However, extensions to Standard SQL add procedural programming language functionality, such as control-of-flow constructs.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] In addition to the standard SQL/PSM extensions and proprietary SQL extensions, procedural and object-oriented programmability is available on many SQL platforms via DBMS integration with other languages.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] The SQL standard defines SQL/JRT extensions (SQL Routines and Types for the Java Programming Language) to support Java code in SQL databases.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] Microsoft SQL Server 2005 uses the SQLCLR (SQL Server Common Language Runtime) to host managed .NET assemblies in the database, while prior versions of SQL Server were restricted to unmanaged extended stored procedures primarily written in C.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] PostgreSQL lets users write functions in a wide variety of languages—including Perl, Python, Tcl, JavaScript (PL/V8) and C.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] A distinction should be made between alternatives to SQL as a language, and alternatives to the relational model itself.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] Below are proposed relational alternatives to the SQL language.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] See navigational database and NoSQL for alternatives to the relational model.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] Distributed Relational Database Architecture (DRDA) was designed by a workgroup within IBM from 1988 to 1994.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] DRDA enables network-connected relational databases to cooperate to fulfill SQL requests.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] An interactive user or program can issue SQL statements to a local RDB and receive tables of data and status indicators in reply from remote RDBs.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] SQL statements can also be compiled and stored in remote RDBs as packages and then invoked by package name.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] This is important for the efficient operation of application programs that issue complex, high-frequency queries.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] It is especially important when the tables to be accessed are located in remote systems.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] The messages, protocols, and structural components of DRDA are defined by the Distributed Data Management Architecture.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] Distributed SQL processing ala DRDA is distinctive from contemporary distributed SQL databases.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] SQL deviates in several ways from its theoretical foundation, the relational model and its tuple calculus.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] In that model, a table is a set of tuples, while in SQL, tables and query results are lists of rows; the same row may occur multiple times, and the order of rows can be employed in queries (e.g., in the `LIMIT` clause).
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] Critics argue that SQL should be replaced with a language that returns strictly to the original foundation: for example, see *The Third Manifesto* by Hugh Darwen and C.J.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] Early specifications did not support major features, such as primary keys.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] Result sets could not be named, and subqueries had not been defined.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] The lack of sum types has been described as a roadblock to full use of SQL's user-defined types.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] JSON support, for example, needed to be added by a new standard in 2016.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] The concept of Null is the subject of some debate.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] The Null marker indicates the absence of a value, and is distinct from a value of 0 for an integer column or an empty string for a text column.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] The concept of Nulls enforces the 3-valued-logic in SQL, which is a concrete implementation of the general 3-valued logic.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] Another popular criticism is that it allows duplicate rows, making integration with languages such as Python, whose data types might make accurately representing the data difficult, in terms of parsing and by the absence of modularity.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] This is usually avoided by declaring a primary key, or a unique constraint, with one or more columns that uniquely identify a row in the table.
[src:drizzle-orm/sql] In a sense similar to object–relational impedance mismatch, a mismatch occurs between the declarative SQL language and the procedural languages in which SQL is typically embedded.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] In computer science, **type safety** is the extent to which a programming language discourages or prevents type errors.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] Type-safe languages are sometimes also called **strongly** or **strictly typed**.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] The behaviors classified as type errors by a given programming language are usually those that result from attempts to perform operations on values that are not of the appropriate data type, e.g. trying to add a string to an integer.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] Type enforcement can be static (catching potential errors at compile time), dynamic (associating type information with values at run-time and consulting them as needed to detect imminent errors), or a combination of both.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] Dynamic type enforcement can often run programs that would be invalid under static enforcement, but at the cost of introducing errors at runtime.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] In the context of static (compile-time) type systems, type safety usually involves (among other things) a guarantee that the eventual value of any expression will be a legitimate member of that expression's static type.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] The precise requirement is more subtle than this — see, for example, subtyping and polymorphism for complications.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] In other words, if a type system is *sound*, then expressions accepted by that type system must evaluate to a value of the appropriate type (rather than produce a value of some other, unrelated type or crash with a type error).
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] A language is type-safe if the only operations that can be performed on data in the language are those sanctioned by the type of the data.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] However, what precisely it means for a program to be "well typed" or to "go wrong" are properties of its static and dynamic semantics, which are specific to each programming language.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] Consequently, a precise, formal definition of type soundness depends upon the style of formal semantics used to specify a language.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] In 1994, Andrew Wright and Matthias Felleisen formulated what has become the standard definition and proof technique for type safety in languages defined by operational semantics, which is closest to the notion of type safety as understood by most programmers.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] or can be reduced towards a value in some well-defined way.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] In other words, the program never gets into an undefined state where no further transitions are possible.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] A number of other formal treatments of type soundness have also been published in terms of denotational semantics and structural operational semantics.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] In isolation, type soundness is a relatively weak property, as it essentially just states that the rules of a type system are internally consistent and cannot be subverted.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] Type safety is usually a requirement for any toy language (i.e., esoteric language) proposed in academic programming language research.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] However, many languages are too big for human-generated type safety proofs, as they often require checking thousands of cases.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] Nevertheless, some languages such as Standard ML, which has rigorously defined semantics, have been proved to meet one definition of type safety.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] Regardless of the properties of the language definition, certain errors may occur at run-time due to bugs in the implementation, or in linked libraries written in other languages; such errors could render a given implementation type unsafe in certain circumstances.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] An early version of Sun's Java virtual machine was vulnerable to this sort of problem.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] Programming languages are often colloquially classified as strongly typed or weakly typed (also loosely typed) to refer to certain aspects of type safety.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] Type safety is closely linked to memory safety.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] Conversely, if the language is memory-safe, it cannot allow an arbitrary integer to be used as a pointer, hence there must be a separate pointer or reference type.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] As a minimal condition, a type-safe language must not allow dangling pointers across allocations of different types.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] But most languages enforce the proper use of abstract data types defined by programmers even when this is not strictly necessary for memory safety or for the prevention of any kind of catastrophic failure.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] Allocations are given a type describing its contents, and this type is fixed for the duration of the allocation.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] This allows type-based alias analysis to infer that allocations of different types are distinct.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] Most type-safe languages use garbage collection.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] Pierce says, "it is extremely difficult to achieve type safety in the presence of an explicit deallocation operation", due to the dangling pointer problem.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] However Rust is generally considered type-safe and uses a borrow checker to achieve memory safety, instead of garbage collection.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] In object-oriented languages type safety is usually intrinsic in the fact that a type system is in place.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] This is expressed in terms of class definitions.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] A class essentially defines the structure of the objects derived from it and an API as a *contract* for handling these objects.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] Each time a new object is created it will *comply* with that contract.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] Each function that exchanges objects derived from a specific class, or implementing a specific interface, will adhere to that contract: hence in that function the operations permitted on that object will be only those defined by the methods of the class the object implements.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] This will guarantee that the object integrity will be preserved.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] Exceptions to this are object oriented languages that allow dynamic modification of the object structure, or the use of reflection to modify the content of an object to overcome the constraints imposed by the class methods definitions.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] Ada was designed to be suitable for embedded systems, device drivers and other forms of system programming, but also to encourage type-safe programming.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] To resolve these conflicting goals, Ada confines type-unsafety to a certain set of special constructs whose names usually begin with the string Unchecked_.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] Unchecked_Deallocation can be effectively banned from a unit of Ada text by applying pragma Pure to this unit.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] It is expected that programmers will use Unchecked_ constructs very carefully and only when necessary; programs that do not use them are type-safe.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] The SPARK programming language is a subset of Ada eliminating all its potential ambiguities and insecurities while at the same time adding statically checked contracts to the language features available.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] SPARK avoids the issues with dangling pointers by disallowing allocation at run time entirely.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] Ada2012 adds statically checked contracts to the language itself (in form of pre-, and post-conditions, as well as type invariants).
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] The C programming language is type-safe in limited contexts; for example, a compile-time error is generated when an attempt is made to convert a pointer to one type of structure to a pointer to another type of structure, unless an explicit cast is used.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] However, a number of very common operations are non-type-safe; for example, the usual way to print an integer is something like `printf("%d", 12)`, where the `%d` tells `printf` at run-time to expect an integer argument.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] In addition, C, like Ada, provides unspecified or undefined explicit conversions; and unlike in Ada, idioms that use these conversions are very common, and have helped to give C a type-unsafe reputation.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] For example, the standard way to allocate memory on the heap is to invoke a memory allocation function, such as `malloc`, with an argument indicating how many bytes are required.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] The function returns a void pointer (`void*`), which the calling code must explicitly or implicitly cast to the appropriate pointer type.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] Pre-standardized implementations of C required an explicit cast to do so, therefore for an allocation of some `struct Foo`, the code `Foo* foo = (struct Foo*)malloc(sizeof(struct Foo))` became the accepted practice.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] `malloc()` returns `void*` which does not need to be explicitly cast in C, but in C++ this casting is made mandatory for type safety.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] It has support for untyped pointers, but this must be accessed using the "unsafe" keyword which can be prohibited at the compiler level.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] It has inherent support for run-time cast validation.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] Casts can be validated by using the "as" keyword that will return a null reference if the cast is invalid, or by using a C-style cast that will throw an exception if the cast is invalid.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] Undue reliance on the object type (from which all other types are derived) runs the risk of defeating the purpose of the C# type system.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] It is usually better practice to abandon object references in favour of generics, similar to templates in C++ and generics in Java.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] The Java language is designed to enforce type safety.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] Anything in Java *happens* inside an object and each object is an instance of a class.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] To implement the *type safety* enforcement, each object, before usage, needs to be allocated.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] Java allows usage of primitive types but only inside properly allocated objects.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] Sometimes a part of the type safety is implemented indirectly: e.g. the class BigDecimal represents a floating point number of arbitrary precision, but handles only numbers that can be expressed with a finite representation.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] The operation BigDecimal.divide() calculates a new object as the division of two numbers expressed as BigDecimal.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] In this case if the division has no finite representation, as when one computes e.g.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] 1/3=0.33333..., the divide() method can raise an exception if no rounding mode is defined for the operation.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] Hence the library, rather than the language, guarantees that the object respects the contract implicit in the class definition.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] Standard ML has rigorously defined semantics and is known to be type-safe.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] However, some implementations, including Standard ML of New Jersey (SML/NJ), its syntactic variant Mythryl and MLton, provide libraries that offer unsafe operations.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] These facilities are often used in conjunction with those implementations' foreign function interfaces to interact with non-ML code (such as C libraries) that may require data laid out in specific ways.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] Another example is the SML/NJ interactive toplevel itself, which must use unsafe operations to execute ML code entered by the user.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] Modula-2 is a strongly-typed language with a design philosophy to require any unsafe facilities to be explicitly marked as unsafe.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] This is achieved by "moving" such facilities into a built-in pseudo-library called SYSTEM from where they must be imported before they can be used.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] The import thus makes it visible when such facilities are used.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] Unfortunately, this was not consequently implemented in the original language report and its implementation.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] There still remained unsafe facilities such as the type cast syntax and variant records (inherited from Pascal) that could be used without prior import.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] The difficulty in moving these facilities into the SYSTEM pseudo-module was the lack of any identifier for the facility that could then be imported since only identifiers can be imported, but not syntax.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] The ISO Modula-2 standard corrected this for the type cast facility by changing the type cast syntax into a function called CAST which has to be imported from pseudo-module SYSTEM.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] However, other unsafe facilities such as variant records remained available without any import from pseudo-module SYSTEM.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] A recent revision of the language applied the original design philosophy rigorously.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] First, pseudo-module SYSTEM was renamed to UNSAFE to make the unsafe nature of facilities imported from there more explicit.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] Then all remaining unsafe facilities where either removed altogether (for example variant records) or moved to pseudo-module UNSAFE.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] For facilities where there is no identifier that could be imported, enabling identifiers were introduced.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] In order to enable such a facility, its corresponding enabling identifier must be imported from pseudo-module UNSAFE.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] No unsafe facilities remain in the language that do not require import from UNSAFE.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] Pascal has had a number of type safety requirements, some of which are kept in some compilers.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] Where a Pascal compiler dictates "strict typing", two variables cannot be assigned to each other unless they are either compatible (such as conversion of integer to real) or assigned to the identical subtype.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] Under strict typing, a variable defined as TwoTypes is *not compatible* with DualTypes (because they are not identical, even though the components of that user defined type are identical) and an assignment of `T1 := D2;` is illegal.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] An assignment of `T1 := T2;` would be legal because the subtypes they are defined to *are* identical.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] However, an assignment such as `T1.Q := D1.Q;` would be legal.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] In general, Common Lisp is a type-safe language.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] A Common Lisp compiler is responsible for inserting dynamic checks for operations whose type safety cannot be proven statically.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] However, a programmer may indicate that a program should be compiled with a lower level of dynamic type-checking.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] A program compiled in such a mode cannot be considered type-safe.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] The following examples illustrates how C++ cast operators can break type safety when used incorrectly.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] In this example, `reinterpret_cast` explicitly prevents the compiler from performing a safe conversion from integer to floating-point value.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] When the program runs it will output a garbage floating-point value.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] The two child classes have members of different types.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] When downcasting a parent class pointer to a child class pointer, then the resulting pointer may not point to a valid object of correct type.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] In the example, this leads to garbage value being printed.
[src:drizzle-orm/type-safety] The problem could have been avoided by replacing `static_cast` with `dynamic_cast` that throws an exception on invalid casts.
[src:drizzle-orm/typescript] TypeScript may be used to develop JavaScript applications for both client-side and server-side execution (as with React.js, Node.js, Deno or Bun).
[src:drizzle-orm/typescript] Multiple options are available for transpiling.
[src:drizzle-orm/typescript] The default TypeScript Compiler can be used, or the Babel compiler can be invoked to convert TypeScript to JavaScript.
[src:drizzle-orm/typescript] TypeScript supports definition files that can contain type information of existing JavaScript libraries, much like C++ header files can describe the structure of existing object files.
[src:drizzle-orm/typescript] This enables other programs to use the values defined in the files as if they were statically typed TypeScript entities.
[src:drizzle-orm/typescript] There are third-party header files for popular libraries such as jQuery, MongoDB, and D3.js.
[src:drizzle-orm/typescript] TypeScript headers for the Node.js library modules are also available, allowing development of Node.js programs within TypeScript.
[src:drizzle-orm/typescript] The TypeScript compiler is written in TypeScript and compiled to JavaScript.
[src:drizzle-orm/typescript] It is licensed under the Apache License 2.0.
[src:drizzle-orm/typescript] Anders Hejlsberg, lead architect of C# and creator of Delphi and Turbo Pascal, has worked on developing TypeScript.
[src:drizzle-orm/typescript] TypeScript was released to the public in October 2012, with version 0.8, after two years of internal development at Microsoft.
[src:drizzle-orm/typescript] Soon after the initial public release, Miguel de Icaza praised the language, but criticized the lack of mature integrated development environment (IDE) support apart from Microsoft Visual Studio, which was unavailable then on Linux and macOS.
[src:drizzle-orm/typescript] As of April 2021 there is support in other IDEs and text editors, including Emacs, Vim, WebStorm, Atom and Microsoft's own Visual Studio Code.
[src:drizzle-orm/typescript] TypeScript 0.9, released in 2013, added support for generics.
[src:drizzle-orm/typescript] TypeScript 1.0 was released at Microsoft's Build developer conference in 2014.
[src:drizzle-orm/typescript] Visual Studio 2013 Update 2 provided built-in support for TypeScript.
[src:drizzle-orm/typescript] Further improvement were made in July 2014, when the development team announced a new TypeScript compiler, asserted to have a five-fold performance increase.
[src:drizzle-orm/typescript] Simultaneously, the source code, which was initially hosted on CodePlex, was moved to GitHub.
[src:drizzle-orm/typescript] On 22 September 2016, TypeScript 2.0 was released, introducing several features, including the ability for programmers to optionally enforce null safety.
[src:drizzle-orm/typescript] TypeScript 3.0 was released on 30 July 2018, bringing many language additions like tuples in rest parameters and spread expressions, rest parameters with tuple types, generic rest parameters and so on.
[src:drizzle-orm/typescript] TypeScript 4.0 was released on 20 August 2020.
[src:drizzle-orm/typescript] While 4.0 did not introduce any breaking changes, it added language features such as Custom JSX Factories and Variadic Tuple Types.
[src:drizzle-orm/typescript] TypeScript 5.0 was released on 16 March 2023 and included support for decorators.
[src:drizzle-orm/typescript] On March 11, 2025, Anders Hejlsberg announced on the TypeScript blog that the team is working on a Go port of the TypeScript compiler to be released as TypeScript version 7.0 later this year.
[src:drizzle-orm/typescript] It is expected to feature a 10x speedup.
[src:drizzle-orm/typescript] On December 2nd, 2025, Daniel Rosenwasser announced on the blog that TypeScript 6.0 will be the last release written in TypeScript itself, and TypeScript 7.0 will be the first Go-based release.
[src:drizzle-orm/typescript] TypeScript originated from the shortcomings of JavaScript for developing large-scale applications both at Microsoft and among their external customers.
[src:drizzle-orm/typescript] Challenges with dealing with complex JavaScript code led to demand for custom tooling to ease developing of components in the language.
[src:drizzle-orm/typescript] Developers sought a solution that would not break compatibility with the ECMAScript (ES) standard and its ecosystem, so a compiler was developed to transform a superset of JavaScript with type annotations and classes (TypeScript files) back into vanilla ECMAScript 5 code.
[src:drizzle-orm/typescript] TypeScript classes were based on the then-proposed ECMAScript 6 class specification to make writing prototypal inheritance less verbose and error-prone, and type annotations enabled IntelliSense and improved tooling.
[src:drizzle-orm/typescript] Syntactically, TypeScript is very similar to JScript .NET, another Microsoft implementation of the ECMA-262 language standard that added support for static typing and classical object-oriented language features such as classes, inheritance, interfaces, and namespaces.
[src:drizzle-orm/typescript] As TypeScript is simply a superset of JavaScript, existing JavaScript can be adapted to TypeScript and TypeScript program can seamlessly consume JavaScript.
[src:drizzle-orm/typescript] The compiler can target all ECMAScript versions 5 and above, transpiling modern features like classes and arrow functions to their older counterparts.
[src:drizzle-orm/typescript] With TypeScript, it is possible to use existing JavaScript code, incorporate popular JavaScript libraries, and call TypeScript-generated code from other JavaScript.
[src:drizzle-orm/typescript] Type declarations for these libraries are usually provided with the source code but can be declared or installed separately if needed.
[src:drizzle-orm/typescript] The TypeScript compiler, named `tsc`, is written in TypeScript.
[src:drizzle-orm/typescript] As a result, it can be compiled into regular JavaScript and can then be executed in any JavaScript engine (e.g. a browser).
[src:drizzle-orm/typescript] The compiler package comes bundled with a script host that can execute the compiler.
[src:drizzle-orm/typescript] It is also available as a Node.js package that uses Node.js as a host.
[src:drizzle-orm/typescript] The compiler is currently being rewritten in Go for version 7.
[src:drizzle-orm/typescript] The compiler can *target* a given edition of ECMAScript (such as ECMAScript 5 for legacy browser compatibility), but by default compiles for the latest standards.
[src:drizzle-orm/typescript] Using plug-ins, TypeScript can be integrated with build automation tools, including Grunt (grunt-ts), Apache Maven (TypeScript Maven Plugin), Gulp (gulp-typescript) and Gradle (TypeScript Gradle Plugin).
[src:drizzle-orm/typescript] TSLint scans TypeScript code for conformance to a set of standards and guidelines.
[src:drizzle-orm/typescript] ESLint, a standard JavaScript linter, also provided some support for TypeScript via community plugins.
[src:drizzle-orm/typescript] However, ESLint's inability to leverage TypeScript's language services precluded certain forms of semantic linting and program-wide analysis.
[src:drizzle-orm/typescript] In early 2019, the TSLint team announced the linter's deprecation in favor of `typescript-eslint`, a joint effort of the TSLint, ESLint and TypeScript teams to consolidate linting under the ESLint umbrella for improved performance, community unity and developer accessibility.
